Welsh MPs don’t want to appear as ‘muppets’
Members of the Welsh National Assembly, known today by the abbreviation AM (Assembly Members), are not entirely satisfied with the suggestion that their title can be changed to MWP (Member of the Welsh Parliament).
The proposal comes as a result of plans to change the name of the National Assembly to the Welsh Parliament.
Representatives from across the political spectrum fear that this could lead to ridicule.
A representative from the Labour Party explained his group was concerned because "it rhymes with Twp and Pwp."
For readers outside Wales: In Welsh, twp means "dusty", and pwp means "poop".
A representative for the Wales party Plaid Cymru said that the group as a whole was "dissatisfied" and that they have suggested alternatives.
A representative of the Welsh section of the Conservative Party said that his group was "open" to the name change, but noted that the pronunciation of the MWP is very close to the word "Muppet", which in addition to being the name of some famous dolls, is also a British slang word for "dust".
In this context, the Welsh letter W is pronounced in a similar manner to the letter U pronounced in the English Yorkshire dialect, more like an "uh" sound.
The Assembly Commission, which is currently developing laws to introduce the name change, said: “It is, of course, the members themselves who have the final say in what name to refer to.”
The Government of Wales Act 2017 gave the Welsh Parliament the authority to change its own name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public hearing showing general support for renaming the National Assembly to the Welsh Parliament.
As for the title of the representatives, the Commission supported WMPs (Welsh Parliament Members), but the alternative MWP received the most support during the public consultation.
Representatives are apparently proposing other options, but getting all parties to come to an agreement could lead to a headache for parliament president Elin Jones, who is scheduled to deliver a legislative draft for the name change in the next couple of weeks.
The legislation surrounding the reform will include other changes to the functioning of the National Assembly, including rules for disqualification of representatives and the design of the committee system.
Representatives have the last vote on what they should be called when debating the legislation.
