"The sea is ours": Bolivia, a land without a coastline, hopes the right will open the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rigged naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings raise a sea-blue flag.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are decorated with the motto: “We have the right to the sea.
It is our duty to recover it.”
The entire inland state of Bolivia still has fresh memories of the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century, and the country longs to once again be able to sail the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps greater than they have been for decades, as Bolivia awaits an International Court of Justice ruling on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
"Bolivia has drive, community spirit and serenity, and of course awaits the result with a positive attitude," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court of Justice on the big screen in many different parts of the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will give its ruling in favor of Bolivia’s claim that Chile – after decades of sporadic negotiations – is committed to negotiating to give Bolivia its own outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president – who faces a controversial re-election campaign next year – has also staked heavily on Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to a return to the Pacific,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court would hardly take Bolivia's side, and that very little would change if it had.
The UN body, which the team of the Netherlands, has no authority to allow them to give away Chilean lands, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The ruling by the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the last arguments were heard implying that the case “was not complicated,” according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And rather than having promoted Bolivia’s cause, the last four years may actually have made things worse.
"The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
She believes that Morales' antagonistic rhetoric has corroded any remaining goodwill on Chile's part.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the negotiations on one point or another, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative at The Hague, rejected the theory that the court's decision came unusually quickly.
On Monday, he said, Bolivia would provide “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new generation’s relationship with Chile” and “end 139 years of disagreement, for the benefit of both parties.”
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – who remains one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – has used the maritime situation as a political cover.
