The Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now a page from the “Sunday Morning” almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago, was the day the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, a discovery that led to the apparatus we know today as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter has been an important part of science since then, and also became part of popular culture via the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: “What in the world is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter. It finds radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you touch these headphones, you can hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: “Let’s say it makes a noise now!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention to which he gave his name lives on.
