According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is for the company to provide resources, process and relevant expertise to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contracted developers to work on the project and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools found on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce something completely new, which will cause their business models to be completely rebranded overnight.
“We don’t ask for your permission.”
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s “mission is to offer commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Although he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will still be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about the next era of the web,” added Berners-Lee.
Bernard Vann: Celebration of the Victoria Cross Recipient of World War I
The only minister of the Church of England to be awarded a Victoria Cross during World War I as a combatant was celebrated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant Colonel and priest Bernard Vann was awarded the honour on 29 September 1918 at the Battle of Bellenglice and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never learned that he was awarded the highest British military award.
A memorial stone was uncovered by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said there was a "great symbolism" in that the stone would be uncovered exactly 100 years after his grandfather's award-winning feat.
According to the London Gazette, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin on 29 September – “through very thick fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns.”
Later, he crashed towards the line of fire and led the line "with great courage" forward before storming a field gun single-handedly and knocking out three of the detachments.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918 – just a month before the war was over.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I knew I could never live up to, but something that makes me humble".
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid down a wreath after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Corps.
