The National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
New research carried out at a Scottish Highlands country estate will reveal how bats use the landscape in search of food.
There is hope that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help design future conservation measures.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brownling and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also perform mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Experts' sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and which species do what.
Then, a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be included in the decision on which measures to introduce, such as planting pastures and how to best care for the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affects breeding sites and habitat restriction.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with flypaper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from house cats.
Bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road as they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, mapping of breeding sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only separate bat reserve at Threave land estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have the perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He emphasizes the importance of mapping the bats before performing maintenance on a property since unwitting destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them, or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species, we simply don’t know how the populations are doing.”
