Europe secures Ryder Cup victory in Paris
Team Europe has won the 2018 Ryder Cup after beating Team USA by a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National outside Paris, France.
The United States has now lost six times in a row on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the throne when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjørn got the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
US star Phil Mickelson, who struggled during much of the tournament, cut his tee-beats in the water at the par-3 16th hole, and had to see himself beaten by Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was brilliant on all his rounds and became 1 of 4 golfers who have ever gone 5-0-0 since the tournament got its current design in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was knocked out 5 and 4 by the lowest ranked player on the European team, Thorbjørn Olesen from Denmark.
The world's top ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to Ian Poulter of England, who may have played his last Ryder Cup final.
With eight Ryder Cups behind him, Spanish Sergio Garcia became the tournament's most-winning European of all time with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t help myself.
It's been a rough year.
I am so grateful that Thomas picked me out and had faith in me.
I'm very, very happy to get the cup back.
It's about the team, and I'm glad I could be of help," said an emotional Garcia after the European win.
He hands over the baton to his compatriot John Ram, who beat American golf legend Tiger Woods 2 and 1 in singles games on Sunday.
“I’m incredibly proud to beat Tiger Woods – I followed that man closely growing up,” said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four of his matches in France and now has a record of 13-21-3 career points in the Ryder Cup.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest golfers ever, who has won 14 major titles, only beaten by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA struggled all weekend to find the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played golf with high precision throughout the tournament.
U.S. team captain Jim Furyk stated after a disappointing performance for his squad, "I'm proud of these guys, they fought.
There were moments this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We threw ourselves.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great team captain.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We will regroup, I will work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup committee and will look to the future.
I love these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their team captain.
You just have to take your hat off.
We were beaten.”
Algal bloom update: Concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Commission on Fish and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decline in red-algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae extends about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are detected about 10 miles (16 km) off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported on or off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Irritation is still reported in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There were no reports of irritation to the airways in northwest Florida during last week.
